WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.520 --> 00:00:03.700
Hi, and welcome to Designing Open Democracy Podcast.

2
00:00:03.700 --> 00:00:11.720
This is actually an auto recording that we had on the 21st of October 2017 that we decided to show to you guys again.

3
00:00:11.740 --> 00:00:19.880
And this event was called Citizens' Democracy, which was hosted by Brian Koo and Nicholas Morange.

4
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:28.420
As for their venue, the venue was gratefully sponsored to us by a co-working space called York Butter Factory at Melbourne.

5
00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:41.220
And the speaker we will be showing you today is Nicholas Gruen, who's a prominent Australian economist, as well as a commentator on economic reforms, innovation and public policy.

6
00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:59.800
He's currently the CEO of Lateral Economics and Economic Consultancy firms, covering economic reform and public policy, as well as a chairman of Open Knowledge Foundation Australia, who supports and empowers those who believe in open knowledge and transparency.

7
00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:06.600
So a common thing you will find in his talk is how, essentially, current mass media is like mental junk food.

8
00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:17.780
And what this leads to is essentially capturing the population's 30-second sound bite of what they observe, rather than the well-considered opinion of the population.

9
00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:25.660
So a way of potentially solving this is through the use of citizen juries, which Hubert will explain in this coming talk.

10
00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:34.800
So let's lead you in with an introduction that he will be speaking about himself and what he wants to explain about this idea of his.

11
00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:40.480
So in 2008, Barack Obama was elected.

12
00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:49.420
The most important thing that was happening at the time was that the world was sliding into the greatest economic catastrophe since the Great Depression.

13
00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:53.460
And the social media was a big deal.

14
00:01:53.480 --> 00:01:57.000
And so we held a policy brainstorming session.

15
00:01:57.020 --> 00:02:00.660
And you might not have heard of this very well.

16
00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:02.840
It didn't get a lot of publicity.

17
00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:11.180
But anyone could make a policy suggestion and they could vote other people's policy suggestion up and down the ladder.

18
00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:21.180
And so we were going to have true internet mediated direct democracy, at least by way of recommendation to the powers that be.

19
00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:38.520
What do you think was the suggestion that came first at a time like that for the US government, the suggestion that won the click baiting competition for voting policy up or down to legalise marijuana?

20
00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:43.160
The second one was to release Barack Obama's birth certificate.

21
00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:45.720
And spare a thought for the Americans.

22
00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:54.900
They have a fairly unique problem that it seems is much less of a problem in any other country, which of course is the abduction of their citizens by aliens.

23
00:02:56.040 --> 00:03:05.900
So that's what came first, second and third in a very early attempt to bring the internet to bring us direct democracy.

24
00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:08.960
So welcome to what I call What's Pop Democracy.

25
00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:11.240
You'll be familiar with it.

26
00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:12.820
We live in it right now.

27
00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:22.580
And one way of summarizing will be to say that that is what the essential philosophy of our democracy is all about.

28
00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:39.500
Of course, you're not forced not to think before you vote, but the whole way in which media works is simply to try to arouse your attention, your emotions, your disgust, your resentment, and so on.

29
00:03:39.500 --> 00:04:01.520
So we are now at a kind of extraordinary point where a policy which was to withdraw from, for the British to withdraw from Europe got up, although it's quite unclear what that meant or in what circumstances it would be regarded as a good idea and what circumstances would not be regarded as a good idea.

30
00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:08.580
Is the vote for Brexit, a vote for Brexit if the European Union won't do a deal?

31
00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:16.940
Is it a vote to simply jump out of the EU and take the tariff wall of the EU presents other countries?

32
00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:21.040
Or is it predicated on the idea that we ought to be able to do some kind of deal?

33
00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:39.800
Is it predicated on the idea that by coming out of Europe, Britain would say 350 million pounds a week, which could then be spent on the NHS, and buses driving around England claimed and so on, quite wrongly, and so on and so forth.

34
00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:50.220
And then we have our friend, Mr. Trump, a kind of, well, it's hard to describe Mr. Trump, but not really like anything we've ever seen before.

35
00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:58.720
Psychopathic, presumably, completely disorganised mental state, and there it is, the President of the United States.

36
00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:16.300
Now, in fact, I want to suggest to you that, just as Australia led the world on lots of things to do with policy, we were one of the world leaders in economic reform, and we did it better than most countries in the 80s, particularly in the 90s, we led the world on this as well.

37
00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:49.600
This is the man who led it, and though his reign is somewhat over now, we lived with the upshot of that, which is that the greatest achievement of the parliament that assembled in 2013 after the 2013 election was the elimination, or was the blasting away of a difficult policy consensus that had been reached over the previous 15 years to price carbon.

38
00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:58.260
How many people in this room would like to have a guess at what damage that does to the budget every year?

39
00:06:03.860 --> 00:06:05.840
Ten billion dollars.

40
00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:12.340
A third of the budget deficit every year because we abolished carbon pricing.

41
00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:18.440
What is significant about that policy is not that I'm against it and most of you will be against it, I think.

42
00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:24.060
What's significant about it is that most parliamentarians were against it.

43
00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:28.880
80, 90 percent of parliamentarians thought it was a completely crazy thing to do.

44
00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:41.140
And somehow this system worked itself into a position of implementing it as the signal achievement of the incoming government, as is happening.

45
00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:48.480
And that's a way in which we beat the Brits to Brexit and the Americans to Donald Trump.

46
00:06:48.500 --> 00:07:00.160
And one analogy I want to suggest to you is what's happening is that our society is being optimized for the things that evolved on the African Savannah.

47
00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:06.260
And I would say this is true of many industries, many aspects of our lives.

48
00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:17.720
And I want to suggest to you that one of the number of things that evolved on the African Savannah was that you didn't eat food that smelled in a way that disgusted you.

49
00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:24.800
You liked clean food, you liked food that was rich with fat, you liked sweet food.

50
00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:26.840
And that's what we've got.

51
00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:38.760
And food that is very close to being nutritious and has certainly been, a lot of loving care has been given to what it is, is now poisonous.

52
00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:42.100
And that's roughly what's happening in democracy.

53
00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:47.760
We are getting pretty much exactly what we're asking for in certain kinds of respects.

54
00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:58.720
That's an uncomfortable thing to say, but otherwise, unless you want to play the game, which most people do, that's all those nasty politicians of We're the Good Guys.

55
00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:03.000
I don't think that will get you anywhere, but that's how the game is played.

56
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.620
We're part of this just as we buy McDonald's handbills.

57
00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:11.040
I want to suggest two very simple ideas to you about democracy.

58
00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:17.760
These both come from a rather patrician fellow, quite right-wing.

59
00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:24.000
They don't have their sort of logical ideas, so you can dispense with whether they're right-wing or left-wing.

60
00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.340
They're basically logical ideas.

61
00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:29.580
Joseph Schumpeter is the man.

62
00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:41.039
He was the Finance Minister of Austria, as our other speaker might know, was a professor at Harvard for quite a long time and a great historian of economics and a great economist himself.

63
00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:50.640
Here are the two ideas that stood out for me when I read the book about 40 years ago and then I reread the two chapters on democracy.

64
00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:52.860
Very simple architectural ideas.

65
00:08:52.960 --> 00:09:02.720
There's the first one that one of the fundamental issues of democracy is to navigate the Cognitive Division of Labor.

66
00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:09.020
And in many senses, the Cognitive Division of Labor is kind of the serpent in paradise.

67
00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:14.840
Because, of course, a Cognitive Division of Labor introduces principal age and problems.

68
00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:22.480
It introduces the need to trust certain people to act on your behalf, meanwhile they have your own interests.

69
00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:26.500
So, that's the first idea.

70
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:31.620
Schumpeter uses the expression leadership.

71
00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:33.240
I'm not going to worry about that too much.

72
00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:40.940
The basic idea I'm taking from it is the idea of a cognitive division like that.

73
00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:45.900
That even quite simple social organizations have to break themselves up.

74
00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:51.480
So, if you look at any club, it's got a treasurer, a secretary, a president, and so on.

75
00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.300
That's basically the idea.

76
00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:56.700
And the second idea is this.

77
00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:07.680
That if you go down to the shop to buy bread, you will engage your rational faculties.

78
00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:09.700
You will know something about what you want.

79
00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:12.220
You'll have a lot of background experience in it.

80
00:10:12.220 --> 00:10:25.020
You will be trying to attend to a practical question, which is, what's the best bread I can get, as far as sort of divided by value of month for month, if you know what I mean.

81
00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:27.680
That's not the world that we're in in politics.

82
00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:42.380
In politics, we actually don't, there's no rational reason for us to vote at all, in terms of our self-interest, because we have an infinitesimal chance of influencing the result.

83
00:10:42.380 --> 00:10:53.440
So we're actually about something else in politics, and politics, I will assert to you, based on this authority and your own experience, is essentially run by emotion.

84
00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:57.480
That's the motive force behind it.

85
00:10:57.720 --> 00:10:58.740
The motive force.

86
00:10:58.740 --> 00:10:59.180
Sorry?

87
00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:00.180
The motive force.

88
00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:00.920
Well, thank you.

89
00:11:01.100 --> 00:11:03.080
Yes, I should investigate the...

90
00:11:03.100 --> 00:11:06.200
I should investigate the etymology of that.

91
00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:09.700
So, those emotions can operate for good.

92
00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:12.920
And I'm going to call these feminine emotions.

93
00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:20.800
And this is the emotion of binding us together from within, as it were.

94
00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:26.780
And there is also something that goes pretty horribly wrong.

95
00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:33.300
And that's typically emotions which take a strongly masculine character.

96
00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:36.440
Now, I'm not saying masculine bad, feminine good.

97
00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:42.940
But I am saying masculine is much more likely to come with some pretty nasty costs.

98
00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:44.900
Feminine can go wrong too.

99
00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:54.560
But at the moment, I want to suggest to you that we have a polity which is massively pushed in the direction of one set of emotions.

100
00:11:55.900 --> 00:12:00.620
So, here is something that somebody once said.

101
00:12:00.620 --> 00:12:06.780
They were a, they are, I suppose, a captain in the Australian Navy.

102
00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:10.740
It was quite a joy to hold those little kids' hands and watch them smile.

103
00:12:10.740 --> 00:12:14.760
You know, who said, well, what's the event that person's talking about?

104
00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:21.720
It's the same event as that expression.

105
00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:33.760
And the first expression was said first, and it was made clear to Commander Norman Banks that it wasn't appreciated by his political masters.

106
00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:45.080
And what happened in our politics is that one particular type of emotion came to dominate.

107
00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:56.000
And the problem is most of the things we're stuck worrying about are things that require quite a lot of thought.

108
00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.340
They'll require compromise and so on.

109
00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:05.340
And we have a style of political discussion which actually makes that very difficult.

110
00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:12.100
It doesn't help that the size of soundbites are kind of collapsing steadily.

111
00:13:12.100 --> 00:13:17.240
And we have a style of politics, which I call politics as culture war.

112
00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:22.020
You know you're on a particular side, you know you're the good guys, and then there are the bad guys.

113
00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:29.620
And we play, you know, we police their speech, we do the whole, it's the works.

114
00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:42.780
So, and then this is then, this is then strengthened by our press, which plays on emotion and all of the toxic kind of emotions.

115
00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:43.960
This is in Britain.

116
00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:46.520
I was in London and I saw that poster.

117
00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:47.960
I was just horrified.

118
00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:53.880
I mean, here are wealthy people tearing up the social contract that allows them to be wealthy.

119
00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:59.820
The rule of law, that they are, they're enemies of the people, a fine, Stalinist expression.

120
00:13:59.820 --> 00:14:06.120
And the same sort of thing has been happening in this country for years and so on.

121
00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:08.460
This is a nice little vignette for you.

122
00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:16.080
Remember when the Indonesians blew away to Australians for smuggling drugs?

123
00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:24.520
And of course, the Daily Telegraph were horrified and orchestrated national outrage that the Indonesians should be served callous.

124
00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:30.340
But of course, when they've been caught, the Daily Telegraph was on the other side.

125
00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:33.760
You know, throw the book at them, that's what they deserve and so on.

126
00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:37.680
So not a word of that, of course.

127
00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:39.980
Power without responsibility.

128
00:14:39.980 --> 00:14:48.740
This is when you have the temerity to say that there should be some regulatory system which holds the media to some kind of account.

129
00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:56.340
And so here we are with politics very much in this state and it's now official.

130
00:14:56.340 --> 00:15:00.000
So what might we do about it?

131
00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.640
That's one of the things we need to do about it.

132
00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:08.620
We need, I think, to rebalance the way what kinds of emotions dominate in political debate.

133
00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:13.380
And I wish to turn to the origins of democracy to talk about that.

134
00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:15.960
I'm not going to talk very much about participation.

135
00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:17.900
I'm going to talk about deliberation.

136
00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:23.540
And there's a whole sort of divide we could talk about there in questions or at some other time.

137
00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:27.000
So here are these two ways of representing.

138
00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:42.800
So if we take Schumpeter's idea that we need a division of labor, but we can't have everyone having a view about everything any more than we would want everyone to have a view about every criminal case that goes before the courts.

139
00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:48.880
Then we need to represent the people and we need to have what I call cognitive elites.

140
00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:56.260
They don't have to be more powerful or more important than anyone else, but they need to spend the time trying to think about the issues.

141
00:15:56.260 --> 00:16:05.540
We can do this by election or we can do it by law, which is the way we do it in juries, which is something like random selection or some similar process.

142
00:16:05.940 --> 00:16:16.040
It comes as a big surprise to a lot of people to know that the idea of having elections being a touchstone of democracy is a fairly recent idea.

143
00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:22.760
It goes back to the French Revolution and the American Revolution in the late 18th century.

144
00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:28.160
Before that, democracy was much more associated with selection by lot.

145
00:16:28.160 --> 00:16:37.840
Going back to Athens, the Athenian boule, European cities like Venice and Lawrence during the Renaissance, juries in court and so on.

146
00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:49.300
And here are some things about the different kind of politics that takes place.

147
00:16:49.300 --> 00:16:56.780
Elections, this is something that the more I've thought about, the more important I think it is, and I never really see people talk about it.

148
00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.220
This is again a very simple logical point.

149
00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:05.819
If you want to represent people by elections, that is a competitive process.

150
00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:14.300
You cannot beat a politician without beating other politicians to the task of representing the people.

151
00:17:14.300 --> 00:17:22.300
And once you become a representative, you then, in your party, try and beat your opponents.

152
00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:29.040
It's competitive and it is aristocratic, and according to both Aristotle and Montesquieu.

153
00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:34.940
Now, it has a democratic sanction because the people voted for it, but think about the people in parliament.

154
00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:53.000
How many of them, how they represent the age profile of the population, they are skewed in a particular way, and how they represent the education profile and the wealth profile of the population, and you can see the idea of it being aristocratic.

155
00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:00.500
Here we have a unitary system where people's main problem is to try and get to an agreement.

156
00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:15.060
In a jury, your job isn't to beat anyone, it's to try and come up with a conclusion that works, and your natural instinct is to compromise it so far as you can manage it to get to some sort of agreement that everyone is happy with.

157
00:18:15.920 --> 00:18:18.300
And it is democratic in this sense.

158
00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:28.860
And here is a Greek word for you, which I think is really a fundamental word, and it doesn't mean freedom of speech, though it's sometimes translated as such, it means equality of speech.

159
00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:50.040
And one of the reasons I would argue that people like Pauline Hanson are doing as well as they are, is that Pauline Hanson, whether you like her or not, is an authentic politician, and people hear their voice much more through Pauline Hanson than they do through the brand management of many of the other parties.

160
00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:55.600
So the idea is then to say, we should be using this kind of mechanism much more.

161
00:18:55.600 --> 00:19:00.760
Now there's been lots of experimentation with these mechanisms.

162
00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:05.740
There's a lot of field work which tells you that they work pretty well, and I won't.

163
00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:10.980
I will now race through some of these things, but I'll just show you this one.

164
00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:13.160
I think this is a really important point.

165
00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:22.800
This was a Citizens' Jury about making Adelaide safe and prosperous, have a good nightlife that was safe.

166
00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:26.400
And imagine that being discussed on the radio.

167
00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:33.600
The six foot two man and the two short women, well, they'd come in on the radio and they'd have a good old barn.

168
00:19:33.600 --> 00:19:34.960
That's how we do it.

169
00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:39.360
And this guy walks in and he goes, oh, I see, I see, there's a problem.

170
00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:40.580
How would I know?

171
00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:43.340
And they rapidly come to a conclusion.

172
00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:55.900
The upshot of this is that juries, the people on Citizens Juries almost invariably report the experience is a fantastically good one.

173
00:19:55.900 --> 00:20:06.020
The Citizens' Jury in Melbourne of the 43 or however many people were on the Citizens' Jury, two or possibly three people stood for local council at the next election.

174
00:20:06.020 --> 00:20:12.680
That gives you some idea of how that, of how generative it is to this kind of activity.

175
00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:22.240
And so what we've got here is the kind of context in which this kind of sentiment might have a better chance.

176
00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:35.480
So I'll skip through that, because I'm getting a wind up, but I will tell you what I want to get at, a sort of utopia for me, or where I would like to, you know, you make me the nebulous dictator, this is what you'll get.

177
00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:37.940
And then I'll talk about how I think we should get there.

178
00:20:37.940 --> 00:20:46.380
I think we should acknowledge that we are in a fantastic world that has been built over the last 200 years since the French and American revolutions.

179
00:20:46.380 --> 00:20:49.840
It's a massive success with some very mousy toxic bits in it.

180
00:20:50.500 --> 00:21:15.020
And so, where the 18th century and the 19th century was about setting up checks and balances between a lower house representing the people and an upper house representing property, I think we should be now moving, and we will now move towards checks and balances between the people as represented by their elected representatives and the people represented as they are in a jury.

181
00:21:15.020 --> 00:21:16.700
Now, how can we get there?

182
00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:29.000
Well, I think it's not that hard to get there, because this would be a fantastically powerful form of political activism.

183
00:21:29.000 --> 00:22:10.020
If you imagine Tony Abbott promising to abolish carbon pricing, and a Citizens' Jury is funded, and a Citizens' Chamber exists, the media would report it, it would be political news, and I have great confidence that when people concentrated on the two policies and found that one was a policy, the one that was for carbon pricing, and the other one was really a kind of set of sound bites to get through a radio interview, and that it was going to cost them, they were going to have to come up with another $10 billion a year of tax money to get rid of this thing, they would have voted for, they would have prevented.

184
00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:18.460
So I think the split would have been something like 60, 70% pro-carbon pricing at a time like that.

185
00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:30.740
That, I think, would be on its own very politically powerful, and a fine piece of legitimation for the sort of world that I want to move towards.

186
00:22:30.740 --> 00:22:42.900
That's a list of things that I'd be prepared to defend at some stage, the qualities of the democracy we have now, and I'll just finish with a couple of points on this.

187
00:22:45.860 --> 00:22:47.320
I've actually intimated this before.

188
00:22:47.320 --> 00:22:52.320
A lot of discussion about democracy involves a magic trick.

189
00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:55.660
The magic trick is that the politicians are letting us down.

190
